            <div class="page" id="page-objective">
                <h1>Project Objective</h1>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <p>This is a tourism website about the Kowloon Walled City. Within this site, visitors will learn
                        about its history, explore related artistic works, and discover nearby travel attractions in the
                        Kowloon area. Through this website, you will experience the unique charm of the Walled City and
                        be captivated by its enduring appeal.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <p>The Kowloon Walled City was one of the most extraordinary urban phenomena in modern history. Yet its
                    story remains fragmented, told through scattered photographs, academic papers, and word of mouth.
                    This project brings that narrative together in one place.</p>

                <h2>Why the Kowloon Walled City?</h2>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <p>Its existence is a myth to many outsiders. It was a place of legend, rumored to be a lawless den
                        of triads and unlicensed dentists. It was a city within a city, with its own rules, economy, and
                        social standards. The Walled Kowloon City is an example of a demolished site where life has
                        forgotten its customs.</p>
                </div>

                <h2>What This Site Will Cover</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Historical Origins</strong> — From Song Dynasty outpost to Qing Dynasty fortress</li>
                    <li><strong>Rise of Anarchy</strong> — The power vacuum that created a lawless enclave</li>
                    <li><strong>City of Darkness</strong> — Unprecedented growth and triad rule (1945-1980s)</li>
                    <li><strong>Life Inside the Walls</strong> — Infrastructure, unregulated services, and community
                        bonds</li>
                    <li><strong>Demolition & Legacy</strong> — The end of the city and what remains</li>
                    <li><strong>The Walled City Today</strong> — Preserved relics, the park, and cultural significance
                    </li>
                </ul>



            </div>


            <div class="page" id="page-why">
                <h1>Why the Kowloon Walled City?</h1>

                <p>To the outside world, the Kowloon Walled City was a legend — a place of lawless myth and urban chaos.
                    But within its walls, it was something far more complex: a self-governing community with its own
                    rules, its own economy, and its own social standards.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <p>The Walled City was a place where the conventional laws of society broke down, yet a different
                        kind of order emerged — one built not by governments, but by the people who lived there.</p>
                </div>

                <p>It was simultaneously a haven and a horror — a refuge for those who had nowhere else to go, and a
                    haven for those who operated outside the law. It thrived without police, without building codes,
                    without any central authority. And yet, it functioned.</p>

                <p>Today, the site is a public park. The buildings are gone, the residents relocated, the chaos
                    silenced. What remains is an abandoned space that has lost the customs and culture that once defined
                    it — a place that lives on only in memory and photographs.</p>

                <p>This project asks: <strong>What can we learn from a place that shouldn't have worked, but
                        did?</strong></p>
            </div>




            <!--more historyyyy-->
            <div class="page" id="page-origins">
                <h1>Historical Origins</h1>
                <p style="font-family:sans-serif; 
                font-size:12px; 
                color:#999; 
                letter-spacing:1px; 
                text-transform:uppercase; 
                margin-bottom:8px;">The Beginning of a dystopian City
                </p>

                <p>The story of the Kowloon Walled City begins long before the anarchy it became famous for. </p>

                <div class="photo">
                    <img src="history old photo.jpg" alt="history photo">
                    <div class="caption">Kowloon Walled City, a fascinating area in Hong Kong, shows us the interesting
                        twists of history, migration, and city life. This crowded settlement was special because it was
                        a part of China right in the middle of the British colony. Its story is one of survival, chaos,
                        and major transformation.</div>
                </div>

                <p>Its roots trace back nearly a thousand years, to a time when the area served as a modest military
                    outpost under the Song Dynasty.</p>

                <h2>Song Dynasty: Monitoring the Salt Trade</h2>
                <p>During the Song Dynasty (960-1279), a military outpost was established in the Kowloon area to monitor
                    and regulate the lucrative salt trade. The site's strategic position near the coast made it an ideal
                    sentry point against pirates and smugglers.</p>

                <h2>Qing Dynasty: The Fortress Walls</h2>
                <p>In the mid-19th century, the Qing government recognized the need for a stronger defensive presence.
                    Construction of a proper walled fortress began, and the Kowloon Walled City was completed in 1847.
                    The fortified structure included a yamen (government office), barracks, and thick stone walls
                    designed to repel invasion.</p>
                <p>However, the fortress was soon tested by internal conflict. Rebellions in the region damaged parts of
                    the structure, and the Qing government's ability to maintain it steadily weakened.</p>

                <h2>1898: The Treaty That Changed Everything</h2>
                <p>The turning point came with the Convention for the Extension of Hong Kong Territory in 1898, which
                    leased the New Territories to Britain for 99 years. The Walled City was initially excluded from the
                    lease — it remained under Chinese jurisdiction. But when British forces moved in, the Chinese
                    officials abandoned the fort, leaving it in a legal grey zone that would persist for nearly a
                    century.</p>

                <div class="timeline">
                    <div class="timeline-item">
                        <div class="year">Song Dynasty (960-1279)</div>
                        <div class="desc">Military outpost established to monitor the salt trade</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="timeline-item">
                        <div class="year">1847</div>
                        <div class="desc">Qing Dynasty completed the walled fortress</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="timeline-item">
                        <div class="year">1898</div>
                        <div class="desc">New Territories that was leased to Britain; Walled City left in legal limbo
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

