            <!--THe risse to anarchy-->
            <div class="page" id="page-anarchy">
                <h1>Rise of Anarchy</h1>
                <p style="font-family:sans-serif; 
                font-size:12px; 
                color:#a6a6a6; 
                letter-spacing:1px; 
                text-transform:uppercase; 
                margin-bottom:8px;">A Lawless Blackhole of Vice</p>

                <p>The transformation of the Walled City from a military fort into a lawless enclave was not sudden — it
                    was the result of decades of political abandonment and neglect.</p>

                <div class="photo">
                    <img src="Aerial view.png" alt="Aerial view of Kowloon Walled City">
                    <div class="caption">Aerial views showing the dense Walled City surrounded by modern Kowloon — a
                        world within a world.</div>
                </div>

                <h2>British Occupation and Retreat</h2>
                <p>After the 1898 treaty, the British initially asserted control over the Walled City but soon found it
                    more trouble than it was worth. The Chinese government still claimed sovereignty, while the British
                    had little interest in governing the small, dilapidated site. By the early 20th century, both sides
                    had effectively walked away.</p>

                <h2>The Power Vacuum</h2>
                <p>With no government willing to take responsibility, the Walled City became a true no-man's-land. No
                    police patrolled its streets. No building codes regulated its construction. No health inspectors
                    checked its factories. Into this vacuum stepped those who thrived in the absence of authority —
                    triads, gamblers, drug operators, and anyone else who preferred to live beyond the reach of the law.
                </p>

                <h2>World War II</h2>
                <p>The Japanese occupation of Hong Kong during World War II further accelerated the Walled City's
                    decline. The occupying forces dismantled parts of the original stone walls for building materials,
                    erasing the last physical remnants of its military heritage. By the end of the war, the Walled City
                    was an open, undefended space — ripe for the chaos that would follow.</p>

                <!-- <div class="share-btn">
                    <button type="button" class="btn share-icon" id="copy-link">share</button>
                </div> -->
            </div>

            <!--CITY OF DARKNESS...bleh -->
            <div class="page" id="page-darkness">
                <h1>City of Darkness</h1>

                <div class="photo">
                    <img src="rundown buildings.jpg" alt="rundown">
                    <div class="caption">'The economy ran sort of on it's own. They had bakeries, barber shops, noodle
                        houses, tea houses, craftsmen, limited use doctors (like non licensed dentists, and traditional
                        medicine), etc. Basically anything you'd find in a city, just crammed into this tiny little area
                        of buildings.' - jgopp, a User in Reddit who has visited the site</div>
                </div>

                <p
                    style="font-family:'Times New Roman', Times, serif; font-size:20px; color:#000000; letter-spacing: spacing 2px;; text-transform:uppercase; margin: bottom 10px;;">
                    Unprecedented Growth (1945-1980s)</p>

                <p>In the decades following World War II, the Walled City underwent a transformation unlike anything the
                    world had seen before. What had been a modest squatter settlement exploded into a towering,
                    self-built megastructure.</p>

                <h2>Refugee Influx</h2>
                <p>After the Chinese Civil War and the establishment of the People's Republic of China in 1949, waves of
                    refugees flooded into Hong Kong. Many found their way to the Walled City, drawn by the absence of
                    rent controls, building regulations, and immigration enforcement. The population swelled from a few
                    hundred to tens of thousands in a matter of years.</p>

                <h2>Triad Rule</h2>
                <p>With the population boom came organized crime. Triad societies — particularly the 14K and Sun Yee On
                    — established firm control over the Walled City. They ran gambling dens, opium dens, and vice
                    operations from the upper floors, while residents on the lower levels tried to live normal lives
                    below. The triads became the de facto authority: they resolved disputes, collected "rent," and
                    maintained a rough order that served their interests.</p>

                <h2>Architectural Anarchy</h2>
                <p>With no building codes to follow, residents built upward with reckless abandon. Structures rose to 14
                    stories or more, connected by a chaotic network of staircases, rooftops, and narrow alleyways.
                    Buildings were constructed inches apart, blocking out sunlight to the lower levels. Electrical
                    wiring and water pipes formed a tangled web on every exterior wall. It was architecture without
                    architects — and it was terrifying, beautiful, and entirely unique.</p>

                <!-- <div class="share-btn">
                    <button type="button" class="btn share-icon" id="copy-link">share</button>
                </div> -->
            </div>





            <!--life inside the walls -->
            <div class="page" id="page-life">
                <h1>Life Inside the Walls</h1>

                <div class="photo">
                    <img src="life.jpg" alt="life">
                    <div class="caption">'The economy ran sort of on it's own. They had bakeries, barber shops, noodle
                        houses, tea houses, craftsmen, limited use doctors (like non licensed dentists, and traditional
                        medicine), etc. Basically anything you'd find in a city, just crammed into this tiny little area
                        of buildings.' - jgopp, a User in Reddit who has visited the site</div>
                </div>

                <p>Despite its fearsome reputation, the reality of daily life inside the Walled City was more nuanced
                    than the headlines suggested. Yes, there was crime and squalor — but there were also schools,
                    temples, post offices, and a strong sense of community.</p>

                <h2>Infrastructure</h2>
                <p>The Walled City had only eight official municipal water taps serving tens of thousands of residents.
                    Water was rationed and carried by bucket to upper floors. Electricity was siphoned from the
                    surrounding city grid through illegal connections — a web of wires that hung like vines from every
                    surface. Despite this, residents had refrigerators, televisions, and even air conditioners.</p>

                <h2>Unregulated Services</h2>
                <p>The Walled City was home to a thriving informal economy. Unlicensed dentists offered cheap dental
                    work in small clinics — many trained in mainland China but unrecognized in Hong Kong. Food factories
                    produced noodles, fish balls, and other goods that were sold outside the walls. Garment workshops
                    churned out clothing. None of these businesses had permits, but they were essential to the local
                    economy.</p>

                <h2>Community and Social Bonds</h2>
                <p>Perhaps the most surprising aspect of the Walled City was its community. Residents looked out for
                    each other. Children played on rooftops while elders chatted in narrow alleyways. Informal mutual
                    aid networks developed — neighbors helped neighbors with childcare, repairs, and mediation. In the
                    absence of government, the people of the Walled City built their own society from the ground up.</p>

                <!-- <div class="share-btn">
                    <button type="button" class="btn share-icon" id="copy-link">share</button>
                </div> -->
            </div>

            <!--when it got destroyed and its legacy-->
            <div class="page" id="page-demolition">
                <h1>Demolition & Legacy</h1>

                <div class="photo">
                    <img src="ruined.jpg" alt="ruined">
                    <div class="caption">The Sino-British Joint Declaration in 1984 laid the groundwork for the city's
                        demolition. The mutual decision by the two governments to tear down the walled city was
                        announced on 14 January 1987.</div>
                </div>

                <p>The end of the Walled City came not with a bang, but with a long, slow process of negotiation,
                    eviction, and finally, demolition.</p>

                <h2>The Sino-British Joint Declaration</h2>
                <p>In 1984, the Sino-British Joint Declaration set the stage for Hong Kong's return to Chinese
                    sovereignty in 1997. With the political future settled, both governments finally found common ground
                    on the Walled City's fate. In 1987, they announced that the site would be cleared and transformed
                    into a public park.</p>

                <h2>Eviction and Demolition</h2>
                <p>The eviction process was prolonged and emotional. Over 33,000 residents were displaced between 1987
                    and 1992. Many had lived in the Walled City their entire lives. Some resisted; others accepted
                    government compensation and resettlement packages. By 1993, the last residents were gone, and
                    demolition began. The buildings — decades of informal architecture — were reduced to rubble in a
                    matter of months.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <p>Demolished in 1993-1994, the Walled City left behind not just physical rubble, but a cultural
                        legacy that continues to fascinate architects, filmmakers, writers, and urbanists around the
                        world.</p>
                </div>

