            <!--THe walled city today or now-->
            <div class="page" id="page-today">
                <h1>The Walled City Today</h1>

                <div class="photo">
                    <img src="kowloon walled city exhinition.jpg" alt="exhibition">

                    <p>Where the Walled City once stood, there is now a peaceful park. But echoes of the past remain...
                        in preserved relics, in the layout of the grounds, and in the cultural memory of a place unlike
                        any other.</p>

                    <!--i might add more photos like here for example/ and yes the stuff here was kinda copy pasted from the internet cause we're runnning out of time TOT-->

                    <h2>Preserved Relics and Artifacts</h2>
                    <p>Several artifacts from the original Walled City have been preserved within the park grounds.
                        These include stone fragments, old signage, and foundations that mark where buildings once
                        stood. They serve as quiet reminders of the dense, chaotic community that existed here.</p>

                    <h2>The Yamen Building</h2>
                    <p>The most significant surviving structure is the Yamen — the old Qing Dynasty government office
                        that predated the Walled City's anarchic era. Restored and preserved, it now stands as the
                        park's centerpiece, a physical link to the site's military origins.</p>

                    <h2>The South Gate</h2>
                    <p>Excavations during the park's construction uncovered the foundations of the original South Gate —
                        the stone entrance to the Qing fortress. These remains have been preserved in situ and are
                        visible to visitors today.</p>

                    <h2>Cultural Icon</h2>
                    <p>Beyond the physical site, the Walled City lives on as a cultural icon. It has inspired countless
                        films, books, video games, and architectural studies. Its image — the impossibly dense, towering
                        blocks connected by a web of pipes and wires — has become a visual shorthand for urban dystopia
                        and the resilience of community.</p>

                    <div class="two-col">
                        <div class="col-box">
                            <h3>Culture Significance</h3>
                            <p>The Walled City represents a unique chapter in urban history — a self-built,
                                self-governing community that operated entirely outside conventional structures of
                                power. Its legacy challenges our assumptions about what a city needs to function.</p>
